				<h2 class="title icon icon0">
					Re: The Expanse
				</h2>
				

						
						
				<div class="content">
					<div id="post_message_1833215">
						<blockquote class="postcontent restore ">
							<div style="margin:20px; margin-top:5px">
<div class="smallfont" style="margin-bottom:2px"><b>Spoiler</b> for <i>response</i>: <input type="button" value="Show" style="width:45px;font-size:10px;margin:0px;padding:0px;" onClick="if (this.parentNode.parentNode.getElementsByTagName('div')[1].getElementsByTagName('div')[0].style.display != 'inline') { this.parentNode.parentNode.getElementsByTagName('div')[1].getElementsByTagName('div')[0].style.display = 'inline'; this.value = 'Hide'; } else { this.parentNode.parentNode.getElementsByTagName('div')[1].getElementsByTagName('div')[0].style.display = 'none';  this.value = 'Show'; }">
</div>
<div class="alt2" style="margin: 0px; padding: 6px; border: 1px inset;">
<div style="display: none;">
 Yeah, but that doesn't actually happen until the second book. There is some &quot;virus&quot; stuff in the first book but that is all alien stuff. Humans are pretty science fact based, which is what makes it even cooler because this alien stuff is so against the rules of anything the humans have experienced they just don't know what the hell to do about it. The story is far more about how human society reacts to the introduction of this stuff. <br />
<br />
When I talk about science fact stuff it has to do with the human ships and forms of travel. Also, the books take into account how long term low gravity environments would affect human physiology. Basically, leaving out the alien stuff, I could very easily imagine human society resembling what is in the book here very closely in 200 years. I could also see very similar results once a destabilizing element like the alien &quot;virus&quot; is introduced.  
</div>
</div>
</div>
						</blockquote>
					</div>

					
				</div>
			</div>
			
